
CHAPTER II.

ABOUT twelve o'clock, that night, was born
the Catherine you saw at Wuthering Heights,
a puny, seven months' child; and two hours
after the mother died, having never recovered
sufficient consciousness to miss Heathcliff, or
know Edgar.

The latter's distraction at his bereavement
is a subject too painful to be dwelt on; its
after effects showed how deep the sorrow sunk.

A great addition, in my eyes, was his being
left without an heir. I bemoaned that, as I
